{"type":"message","id":"38e3ea54","parentId":"d9592027","timestamp":"2026-04-14T10:00:56.699Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me compare the current state (10:00 UTC) against the last known state from heartbeat-state.json (last report at 09:55 UTC):\n\n**Last known state (09:55 UTC):**\n- activeSessions: [] (empty)\n- notableEvents: Persistent sessions cleared to 0, Telegram delivery BLOCKED\n- blockers: Telegram gateway timeout\n- knownFailures: subagent:8bffa95f pre-existing\n\n**Current state (10:00 UTC) from sessions_list:**\n\nActive master-orchestrator sessions:\n1. `cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` — status: running — DTLX 5p Progress Report (THIS cron) — startedAt: 1776160825738\n\n\n2. `cron:ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7` — status: running — 5p Progress Report — startedAt: 1776154374281\n3. `cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` — status: running — Agent Status to Lead — startedAt: 1776159919658\n4. `telegram:group:-5163901258` — status: running — QLHV ecosystem — updatedAt: 1776159028347\n\nI also see a failed direct message to 6053576134 that was already in progress before, and a cron task marked as done with a heartbeat. There are also completed sessions from the direct and group communications, plus several failed subagents scattered across different times—some from 07:12, others from 06:55, and one from 06:14.\n\nLooking at the current state at 10:00 UTC, the main changes are the cron:6f3323ef task now actively running, and the QLHV group session showing as running again after being marked done at 07:12 UTC. The other monitoring sessions are stable and still running as expected. I'm noticing that the QLHV group session had ended earlier at 07:12 UTC but has reappeared as running with a recent update timestamp at 09:30 UTC, which means it's likely been restarted or recreated since then—this represents a genuine change in session state that I should flag in the report. I'm checking the timestamps more carefully—the heartbeat messages in the group session are just system heartbeats, not new user activity. The actual change from the last report is that `telegram:group:-5163901258` went from ended back to running, so I should include that in the DTLX report and send it to the group.\n\nNow I'm deciding what to put in the active sessions count. I need to distinguish between the cron sessions that are monitoring crons (which are part of the reporting infrastructure) versus the QLHV group session, which is the actual ecosystem being monitored. Looking at the previous report from 09:20, it counted 4 active sessions including the QLHV group, so I should follow that same format and include the 3 monitoring crons plus the QLHV group for a total of 4 active sessions.\n\nThe main change I'm tracking is that the QLHV group session has gone from done back to running, which is a status flip. There's also a pre-existing failed session I should note. The pipeline remains healthy with no new failures, though I notice the Telegram gateway timeout that was flagged in the last heartbeat state file doesn't seem to be reflected in the current session data—the group session appears to be running normally now, suggesting the gateway issue may have resolved itself.\n\nSo my report captures the return of the QLHV group session, the pre-existing failed subagent that's still present, and confirms all three cron jobs are running stable.","thinkingSignature":"b22213ebcbb0c8fa3b2804f4f302a40a4996701fdbe272d5e8f7500afc83f999"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lxvubor25za7_1","name":"sessions_send","arguments":{"sessionKey":"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5163901258","message":"🟡 Orbis-DTLX — 5p Update | 10:00 UTC 14 Apr\n\nChanges detected:\n• telegram:group:-5163901258 (QLHV ecosystem) — back to running — was ended at 07:12 UTC, now active again\n• 3 monitoring crons: cron:ed2d0b5d ✅ cron:6f3323ef ✅ cron:e7885813 ✅ — all running stable\n\nPipeline: HEALTHY ✅\n